**[lint-style]** reported by [reviewdog](https://github.com/reviewdog/reviewdog) :dog:
```suggestion (GradedMonoid.mk i a).snd = a := rfl ```
`Type _` is generally a bad idea, you should use `Type*` wherever you can.

I think you can remove the need for these if you instead add:
```lean
@[ext]
theorem gradedMonoid_eq_of_cast {Î“ : Subgroup SL(2, â„¤)} {a b : GradedMonoid (ModularForm Î“)}
    (h : a.fst = b.fst) (h2 : mcast h a.snd = b.snd) : a = b := by
  obtain âŸ¨i, aâŸ© := a
  obtain âŸ¨j, bâŸ© := b
  cases h
  exact congr_arg _ h2
```
which is the approach I used for tensor powers

Sorry if this is a stupid question, but I just want to check I understand. You're saying using this I can get rid of `type_eq` and `cast_eq_mcast`, but I then also need to change the `hEq` lemmas bellow to lemmas about `mcast` instead. For it work like in the tensor powers.
Yes, that is indeed what I mean
Can you put these in the file where `GradedMonoid.GOne` is defined?
Can you create a separate `NatCast (ModularForm Î“ 0)` instance first? Ideally you'd build it up from `SlashInvariantForm` to have a nice defeq.
Sure, I did this for `IntCast` instead, since I guess thats the better instance to have?
I think we need both for defeqs?
Oh so you mean make each of them an separate instance and I guess add some lemma saying they agree?
There's no need to add the lemma that says they agree, that'd handled automatically by existing lemmas in mathlib.
alrighty, done! I didn't quite build it up from Slashinvariantform, but added a lemma saying they agree. But maybe thats a bad idea? I'm not yet sure what the problems would be of doing it this way.

You've got a few repetitive proofs here that could be avoided like this:
```suggestion
theorem hEq_of_mcast_eq {Î“ : Subgroup SL(2, â„¤)} (h : a = b)
    {f : ModularForm Î“ a} {g : ModularForm Î“ b} (H : âˆ€ x, f x = g x) : HEq f g := by
  apply heq_of_cast_eq (type_eq Î“ h)
  rw [cast_eq_mcast h]
  ext1
  simp [H]

theorem hEq_one_mul (k : â„¤) {Î“ : Subgroup SL(2, â„¤)} (f : ModularForm Î“ k) :
    HEq ((1 : ModularForm Î“ 0).mul f) f :=
  hEq_of_mcast_eq (zero_add k) fun _ => by simp
```
I think this is basically the same as https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/9164#discussion_r1432765465, but my version avoids the HEq entirely.

(this will also be useful for building a `GAlgebra` instance, I would guess)
I went ahead and did this for you :)
Oh thank you! it looks a lot cleaner now :)

Ideally the statement of these would be
```suggestion
@[simp]
lemma natCast_coe (Î“ : Subgroup SL(2, â„¤)) (n : â„•) :
    â‡‘(n : ModularForm Î“ 0 ) = n := rfl

@[simp]
lemma intCast_coe (Î“ : Subgroup SL(2, â„¤)) (z : â„¤) :
    â‡‘(z : ModularForm Î“ 0) = z := rfl
```
Note that `by rfl` is almost always an antipattern, you should prefer plain `rfl` unless it times out.

With my suggestion about `const`, this becomes
```suggestion
instance (Î“ : Subgroup SL(2, â„¤)) : NatCast (ModularForm Î“ 0) where
  natCast n := const n

instance (Î“ : Subgroup SL(2, â„¤)) : IntCast (ModularForm Î“ 0) where
  intCast z := const z
```
I've split these results to #9227, which catches a handful of similar missing statements.
